				A comment on third parties. I have been hearing for a while that we need more than a two party system. If you simply look at other nations that have this system, you can easily see the disaster it could lead to in this country. Basically, we use a Primary System and a General Election with an Electorate system for a reason that makes a lot of sense. <br /><br />Take for example a country like Spain, Italy, or France. They are all small countries, in such, there really are no as many opposing views as there are here, and you certainly do not find the nutcase fringe groups the way you do here. In these countries, they will have say a six way election. When the votes are counted, if their is a clear winner, then it is done, he is sworn in and life moves on. However, if it is too close to call, they will take say the top two candiates and have a run off election, with the winner of that vote taking the prize. This works fine there, and we even use this procedure in State and county/city elections here.<br /><br />The problem with using this system in a country with hundreds of millions of people is quite simple. Say we have six candidates running. four of them are fairly sane middle of the road guys, two each slightly left and right of each other, and then two VERY extreme right and left candiates rounding out the six. There is a very good possibility that the voters on both sides could end up splitting their votes around the four candidates, say 15% each, 30% for each party, while the two far extreme candidates end up splitting the remaining 40% between them. This would trigger a run off between the two extremists, and suddenly we are faced with a choice between to nutscases. We will say for arguments sake, that one of the two isn't quite as crazy, and the country slides over to him with say 60% of the vote. It would appear as if he recieved a landslide victory. This of course would not truly be the case. Now we would be left as an electorate with a fanatical candidate, wishing we had rallied together behind two of the mainstream candidates rather than splitting between the four, as they would have recieved 30% each, knocking the other two with 20% off of the ballot. We have our primary system as that is our lead up to the run off in the General Election.<br /><br />This also is why our Nation is NOT NOT NOT a pure Democracy. We are a Federalist Republic, and the reason for this is very simple, and very logical. Although we do govern ourselves, the Forefathers, in VERY GOOD WISDOM, built into the Constitution protections against us directly making policies as a people. We have the Legislature who writes our laws, the Executive Branch that signs and PRESDIES over our laws, and the Judicial that decides the Constitutionality of these laws. The reason is very simple. Say we all have little voting boxes in our house, like some suggest we should have. Tomorrow, a nuclear bomb or Nucyalur as GW would say (did you like that one Kevin? LOL) say one goes off in NY, and all initial evidence points to Russia as the culprit. Well the reponse to a nuclear attack on this country will be a nuclear counter attack. So the vote is put to the people directly, we all hit our yes button out of sheer anger, the ICBM's launch, and poof WWIII. We then find out a couple of days later that oops... we were wrong, it wasn't Russia.. OH FUCK! So in a Federalist system, we elect leaders, and entrust them to make these hard decisions after well thought out deliberation. It is that simple.<br />
